  ARRAY['Unsecured — no security deposit needed','Bad credit accepted (300+ FICO)','Reports to all 3 bureaus monthly']::text[],
  ARRAY['Unsecured credit cards for bad and rebuilding credit — no security deposit required, unlike secured cards at other issuers','Some cards offer 1% cash back on eligible purchases, which is uncommon for the bad-credit card segment','Reports to Equifax, Experian, and TransUnion monthly — responsible use builds credit history from day 1']::text[],
  ARRAY['Annual fees of $0–99 are charged upfront and may reduce your initial credit limit — read the terms before applying','High APRs (typically 25–30%+) — carrying a balance is very expensive and erases any cash back benefit','Approval terms vary widely — the same applicant may see different fees and limits depending on their pre-screened offer']::text[],
  '{"cost":6.2,"features":5.8,"ux":7.4,"support":6.4}'::jsonb,
  'The best unsecured option for rebuilding bad credit without a deposit',
  'Credit One Bank is the only major US card issuer that focuses almost entirely on unsecured credit cards for bad and fair credit — no security deposit is required, unlike secured cards at Discover or Capital One. Most cards offer 1% cash back on eligible purchases, which is uncommon for this segment. The catch: annual fees between $0 and $99 are charged upfront (sometimes reducing the initial credit limit), APRs run 25–30%+, and the approval process is inconsistent — the same applicant may receive wildly different terms depending on their specific credit profile and which pre-screened offer they responded to.',
